<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-615-217  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 615 217.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Nov 12 1990 n616 p122(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>More visas for skilled aliens. (a new immigration reform billexpands the number of visas issued to skilled immigrants,including engineers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bellinger, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>President Bush signs a new immigration reform bill that increasesthe number of visas that can be issued to skilled immigrants,including engineers.andP;  Analysts say the caps set in theemployment-based immigrant category will be more than doubled from54,000 to 140,000, although a 65,000-person limit is set by thebill on temporary skilled immigrants; previously there was nolimit on this category.andP;  American Immigration Lawyers Associationpolicy assistant Jennifer Eisen says the law will help US businessbe more competitive; the association favors looser immigrationlaws.andP;  The American Engineers Association says the law will hurtUS engineers by flooding a depressed job market with more jobseekers.andP;  The categories into which engineer visas are placed bythe bill are priority workers, advanced-degree holders, skilledand unskilled workers, investors and special immigrants.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EngineeringEmployment OpportunityGovernment RegulationLegislationInternationalEmigration and immigration law.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>